    <sec>
      <title>Raw SNV calls</title>
      <p>For HCV run 1 and HCV run 2, both ShoRAH and VarScan detected all true SNVs, i.e. the false negative rate was zero (TableÂ <xref ref-type="table" rid="T3">3</xref>), while LoFreq called all but one true SNV in each run. VarScan, however, also called up to 206 (run 1) and 826 (run 2) false positives, more than seven times as many as ShoRAH. More errors were incorrectly identified as SNVs for HCV run 2 compared to HCV run 1 by both VarScan and ShoRAH, indicating a higher error rate for HCV run 2. VarScanâs recall was greater than ShoRAHâs for the HIV data, with 93% of true SNVs identified, compared to 81% for ShoRAH. However, ShoRAHâs recall was greater than LoFreqâs, which only identified 64% of true SNVs. </p>
      <p>For the HIV sample, all of ShoRAHâs false negatives had true population frequencies under 0.5%, while one of VarScanâs false negatives had a true population frequency of 11.9% (see also FigureÂ <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F2">2</xref>a: recall values less than one indicate false negatives). Upon inspection of the alignment and the VarScan file, this appeared to be the result of confusion in reporting positions with more than one variant allele. Most of LoFreqâs false negatives were very low frequency (under 1%), with three having true population frequencies of under 6%. VarScanâs superior recall was accompanied by a high number of false positive calls â over the reference 766bp considered, 732 false positive SNVs were also called. By comparison, ShoRAH only made two false positive calls (TableÂ <xref ref-type="table" rid="T3">3</xref> and FigureÂ <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F2">2</xref>b). Overall, LoFreq exhibited an exceptionally low false positive rate. For the HCV runs, one unique false positive was identified in each run, while no false positives were called by LoFreq for the HIV data.</p>
