      <p>In particular, <italic>P</italic> (<italic>Y</italic>â=â<underline>1</underline> | <italic>H</italic>â=â<underline>0</underline>) = <italic>Ïµ</italic><sup><italic>d</italic></sup> and <italic>P</italic> (<italic>Y</italic> = <underline>1</underline> | <italic>H</italic> = <underline>1</underline>)â=â(1 â <italic>Ïµ</italic>)<sup><italic>d</italic></sup>.</p>
      <p>In order to assign the read correctly, we need to decide whether the observed read, <italic>Y</italic>â=â<underline>1</underline>, is more likely to originate from the minor haplotype <italic>H</italic>â=â<underline>1</underline> without error or from the major haplotype <italic>H</italic>â=â<underline>0</underline> through (multiple) errors. This decision represents a crucial step in the iterative probabilistic assignment of reads to haplotypes within ShoRAH â if the constituent reads of a low frequency true haplotype are just as likely to originate from a higher frequency haplotype through sequencing errors, then they may be incorrectly assigned to the higher frequency haplotype. In this case, the low frequency haplotype falls below the limit of haplotype detection, and may not be represented in the final set of clustered reads.</p>
      <p>Based on this model, the assignment will be correct if:</p>
