      <p>For noise levels <italic>Ïµ</italic> below this upper bound, we would assign the reads correctly. For <italic>d</italic>â=â1, the condition is <italic>Ïµ &lt; f</italic>, and for <italic>Ïµ</italic> and <italic>f</italic> small, it is approximately <italic>Ïµ</italic><sup><italic>d</italic></sup>â<italic>&lt;âf</italic>. Thus for a given per nucleotide sequencing error rate, the frequency limit for haplotype detection decreases as the number of true SNVs observed within a read increases.</p>
      <p>In reality, the process of haplotype inference is of course more complicated than presented here â our simplified argument is designed to merely demonstrate in a quantitative way that by observing the co-occurrence of variant sites, more power can be achieved when calling low frequency haplotypes (and hence SNVs) than by considering variant sites independently.</p>
