    <sec>
      <title>Strand bias test</title>
      <p>We assume that at any given genomic position, the number of forward reads carrying a variant follows a beta-binomial distribution. More formally, let <italic>F</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> and <italic>R</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>, respectively, denote the total number of forward and reverse reads covering position <italic>i</italic>. The fraction of forward reads is <italic>Î¼</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>â=â<italic>F</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub><italic>/</italic>(<italic>F</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>â+â<italic>R</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>). We define <italic>n</italic><sub><italic>ib</italic></sub> as the total number of reads (forward and reverse) covering the variant base <italic>b</italic> at sequence position <italic>i</italic>. The number of forward reads carrying variant <italic>b</italic> at position <italic>i</italic> is modelled by the beta-binomial random variable <italic>X</italic><sub><italic>ib</italic></sub>â~âBetaBin(<italic>n</italic><sub><italic>ib</italic></sub>, <italic>Î¼</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub>, Ï) such that 0 â¤ <italic>X</italic><sub><italic>ib</italic></sub> â¤ <italic>n</italic><sub><italic>ib</italic></sub> and</p>
